<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">10478451</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>1999</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>02</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2013</Year><Month>11</Month><Day>21</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Print">0916-8451</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Print"><Volume>63</Volume><Issue>7</Issue><PubDate><Year>1999</Year><Month>Jul</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Bioscience, biotechnology, and biochemistry</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Biosci Biotechnol Biochem</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Muscle hypertrophy in rats fed on a buckwheat protein extract.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>1242</StartPage><EndPage>1245</EndPage><MedlinePgn>1242-5</MedlinePgn></Pagination><Abstract><AbstractText>Growing rats were examined for the influence of a buckwheat protein diet on muscle weight and protein. In experiment 1, the rats were fed on a diet containing either casein or a buckwheat protein extract (BWPE) as the protein source (10%, 20% or 30%) for 5 wk. The relative weights (g per kg of body wt) of the gastrocnemius, plantaris and soleus muscles were higher in the BWPE-fed animals than in the casein-fed ones, but were unaffected by the dietary level of protein. These differences were not associated with growth. In experiment 2, the rats were fed on either a casein or BWPE diet at the 20% protein level for 5 wk. BWPE intake significantly elevated the gastrocnemius muscle weight, carcass protein and water, and reduced carcass fat. These results demonstrate that BWPE consumption causes muscle hypertrophy, elevates carcass protein and water, and reduces body fat.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kayashita</LastName><ForeName>J</ForeName><Initials>J</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Kissei Pharmaceutical Company, Matsumoto, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><Last